04729nam a22006495i 9780804792608DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047926087 a10.1515/97808047926082doi  a(DE-B1597)563800  a(OCoLC)1198931233  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBJ324 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a1701 aGubser, Michael D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Far Reaches :bPhenomenology, Ethics, and Social Renewal in Central Europe /cMichael D. Gubser. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Solicitude of the Father -- t2. A True and Better I: Edmund Husserl's Call for Worldly Renewal -- t3. Phenomenology without Reduction: The Realism of the Original Phenomenological Movement -- t4. The Blueprint of a New Heart: Max Scheler and the Order of Love -- t5. Philosophy en plein air: Interwar Social and Ethical Phenomenology -- t6. The Point of View of Life: Czechoslovak Phenomenology through the Prague Spring -- t7. The Far Reaches: Jan Patočka's Transcendence to the World -- t8. The Definitive No: Phenomenology and Czechoslovak Resistance to Impersonal Power -- t9. The Radiation of Humanity: Karol Wojtyła's Phenomenological Personalism -- t10. The Light of Values: Phenomenological Ramifications in Polish Dissidence -- tConclusion: Why Phenomenology Matters as a Social Philosophy -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen future historians chronicle the twentieth century, they will see phenomenology as one of the preeminent social and ethical philosophies of its age. The phenomenological movement not only produced systematic reflection on common moral concerns such as distinguishing right from wrong and explaining the status of values; it also called on philosophy to renew European societies facing crisis, an aim that inspired thinkers in interwar Europe as well as later communist bloc dissidents. Despite this legacy, phenomenology continues to be largely discounted as esoteric and solipsistic, the last gasp of a Cartesian dream to base knowledge on the isolated rational mind. Intellectual histories tend to cite Husserl's epistemological influence on philosophies like existentialism and deconstruction without considering his social or ethical imprint. And while a few recent scholars have begun to note phenomenology's wider ethical resonance, especially in French social thought, its image as stubbornly academic continues to hold sway. The Far Reaches challenges that image by tracing the first history of phenomenological ethics and social thought in Central Europe, from its founders Franz Brentano and Edmund Husserl through its reception in East Central Europe by dissident thinkers such as Jan Patočka, Karol Wojtyła (Pope John Paul II), and Václav Havel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEthicsxHistoryx20th centuryxEurope, Central. 0aEthics, Modernx20th century. 0aPhenomenologyxHistoryx20th century. 0aPhilosophy, Europeanx20th centuryxEurope, Central. 4aEastern Europe. 4aGermany. 4acritique of liberalism and totalitarianism. 4adissidents. 4aethics. 4aintellectual history. 4aphenomenology. 4apolitical theory. 4asocial theory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479260840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804792608423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804792608.jpg  